Digitalization of building plans in Bavaria¶

MS1: Develop scraping tool for Bauleitpläne in Bavaria¶

For this project, we worked scraping the GeoBayern Services API. We downloaded metadata: information about the Stadt, year of the building plan, and the links. We used the column 'URL zur Legende' to download the building plans. The criteria for this was that the columns 'URL zur Raster' contained only the raster image in some cases, and in others the same PDF as the column we used.

Each PDF was downloaded and split into images to parse the content more easily. Therefore, we will be working with two datasets:

  • metadata: each row is a BP. Information of the year, Gemeinde, the links.
  • bp_text: each row is a page of a BP. Text content of that page.
In [ ]:
metadata = pd.read_csv('./data/proc/building_plans/metadata/building_plans_metadata.csv')
bp_text = pd.read_json('./data/proc/building_plans/text/bp_text.json')

Additionally, we downloaded a dataframe of Bayern Gemeinde geographical information. This dataframe is not official, but it is useful to get a list of the Gemeinden in Bavaria to compare the coverage in the geoservices API.

In [ ]:
geo_data = gpd.read_file('./data/final/bavaria_geodata.geojson',
                   sep=';')

#Processing the format of the names.

geo_data['gem_name_short'] = geo_data['gem_name_short'].apply(lambda x: ', '.join(x))

MS2: Enhance current OCR-tool¶

The second goal was to improve the OCR tool. We did so by using a different parser: instead of Tika, the package easyocr. To use it, we also transformed the pdfs into jpgs where each image is a page of the PDF.

Therefore, to get the count of parsed building plans we need to do some processing. We will create the column id in the bp_text to uniquely identify each building plan instead of pages.

In [ ]:
bp_text['id'] = bp_text['filename'].str.extract(r'(\d+)_\d+\.jpg')
bp_text['id'] = pd.to_numeric(bp_text['id'], errors='coerce')

Now, we make a list without duplicates to get the unique ID of the PDFs.

MS3: Investigate if there is a specialised LLM for planning text and proof of concept and fact check output¶

Lastly, we investigated a LLM agent that can be used to extract the information from the building plans. We used the LlamaIndex GPT access to build a prompt and ask individually each page for the information.

First, we select an example of one page of a building plan that contains references to the items we want to extract info from and save it in the folder text_bplans.

In [ ]:
example_archive = bp_text[bp_text['filename'] == '8784_0.jpg']
content = example_archive['content']
content = content.astype(str)

content.to_csv('./data/final/bplan/text_bplans/8784_0.txt', header=None, index=None, sep='\t', mode='w')

Next, we need to load the LLM model and embedding from the API. To do so, you just have to set your keys and endpoint in the function load_models from the module agent_extraction.

In [ ]:
OPENAI_API_KEY =  "your_openai_key"
OPENAI_ENDPOINT = "your_openai_endpoint"

agent_extraction.load_models(AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT = OPENAI_ENDPOINT,
                             AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY = OPENAI_API_KEY)

Next, we load the text in the folder where the example building plan is stored.

In [ ]:
index = agent_extraction.load_data('./data/final/bplan/text_bplans')

Following this we define the template prompt for the query. In the prompt we provide information and context regarding the text and how the information should appear.

In [ ]:
# Define a custom prompt
template = (
    "Im folgenden geht es um den Wert {keyword}.\n"
    "Extrahieren Sie den entsprechenden numerischen Wert aus dem Text.\n"
    "Der Output wird erwartet in folgender Form: {keyword_short}: Zahl Maßeinheit.\n"
    "Wenn der Wert nicht gefunden werden kann, antworte 'None'.\n"
    "---------------------\n"
    "Siehe die folgenden Beispiele:\n"
    "Input: 'wird für die gfz die höchstgrenze von 1,2 festgesetzt' = Output: 'gfz: 1,2'\n"
    "Input: 'setzt eine grund / geschossflächenzahl von 0,4 / 0,5 fest' = Output: 'gfz: 0,5'\n"
    "---------------------\n"
    "Hier ist der Text: {context_str}\n"
)

prompt_tmpl = PromptTemplate(template)

We then define the format of the prompt: the keywords it should look for and their short abbreviation.

In [ ]:
partial_prompt_tmpl = prompt_tmpl.partial_format(keyword="Geschossflächenzahl",
                                                 keyword_short = "GFZ")

Then we use the query engine to extract info.

In [ ]:
query_engine = index.as_query_engine(
        text_qa_template=partial_prompt_tmpl,
        )

response = query_engine.query("Was ist die Geschoßflächenzahl?")

This agent proves to be an exceptionally potent tool for extracting information from PDFs. Not only can we request specific details, such as the Geschoßflächenzahl, and receive accurate outputs, but we can also seek broader information related to structural use metrics.

In [ ]:
query_engine = index.as_query_engine()
response = query_engine.query("What are the measurements for each element of the structural use?")
print(response)

The measurements for each element of the structural use include the following:
- For the MI area: GRZ (floor area ratio) is up to 0.6, GFZ (site area ratio) is up to 1.2, and the maximum number of floors is determined by the building height.
- For the GE and GEA areas: GRZ is up to 0.8, GFZ is up to 2.4, and the maximum number of floors is determined by the building height, with exceptions for technically necessary subordinate building parts.

Hence, Azure OpenAI serves as a Language Model (LLM) that aligns with our objectives. Although it may not be a specialized agent, it demonstrates an ability to comprehend German building plans and effectively extract the pertinent information required for our project.
